			<description><![CDATA[<p>
Join Codecademy&#39;s design team and help create the best educational experience online.</p>
<p>
As a product designer at Codecademy, you&#39;ll be involved in the product development process from start to finish. From brainstorming entirely new products to designing elegant flows &amp; beautiful interfaces, you&#39;ll exercise your full range of product, interaction, and visual design skills on a daily basis.</p>
<p>
You&#39;ll enjoy a high level of ownership of the products you work on. You&#39;ll partner with engineering, community, and data analysis to build and iterate on our products. We&#39;re looking for someone who sweats the details and is ready to tackle any design challenge that comes up between concepting and launching a product.</p>
<p>
Your work will empower millions of people worldwide to learn how to code and create something. Together, we can redesign education and create the best online learning experience.</p>
<p>
<strong>Responsibilities</strong></p>
<p>
- Make high-level contributions to product strategy by concepting future products and improving existing products<br />
- Take broad, conceptual ideas and turn them into elegant flows &amp; simple, intuitive interfaces<br />
- Work with engineers and oversee the building of products you design<br />
- Review portfolios and help grow the Codecademy design team</p>
<p>
<strong>Requirements</strong></p>
<p>
- A portfolio featuring great interaction design for apps<br />
- Ability to clearly communicate and discuss design decisions<br />
- Clean and elegant design aesthetic (from product to interaction to visual)<br />
- Strong eye for typography, layout, and color<br />
- Proficiency with your favorite tools (e.g. Photoshop, Illustrator, pen/paper&hellip;)<br />
- Understanding of how a design would be implemented in code (HTML, CSS, JavaScript).</p>
<p>
<strong>Sound like you? To apply, send a link to your portfolio with a brief introduction.</strong></p>
<p>
<em>A resume is NOT required; you can use a blank document.</em></p>
<p>
&nbsp;</p>
